<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLOTHESLINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARYLOU LUTHER , Luther, a Times Syndicated columnist, welcomes questions 
from readers. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q: I will be attending several formal events this spring and need a new evening 
gown. What's new, and right for a 5-foot-6 38-year-old? I wear a 38-C bra so 
don't suggest a strapless dress or one with a bustier as they only accentuate 
my big bosom. 
</P>
<P>
 -- P.A.W. 
</P>
<P>
A: But that's what you're supposed to do this season. The most up-to-the-minute 
look for evening is the hourglass figure. After years of exile, curves are once 
more fashionable. It's a look right out of "Dangerous Liaisons" and one given a 
big push -- and push-up -- by Paris designer Yves Saint Laurent (illustrated 
here) in his latest haute couture collection. It could be the first fashion 
trend ever inspired by plastic surgery. 
</P>
<P>
If you don't feel comfortable in a bustier or strapless gown, look for one with 
a scooped-out neckline. MARYLOU LUTHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
