<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
'Prelude' Not Burned Out: A New York preview performance of "Prelude to a 
Kiss," starring Timothy Hutton, went on as scheduled Thursday night after an 
early morning fire in the dressing rooms of the Helen Hayes Theatre destroyed 
the majority of the costumes for the play, which is scheduled to make its 
Broadway debut Tuesday. A production spokesman said new costumes and dressing 
room arrangements were hurriedly prepared during the day, and that all the 
theaters on West 44th Street, where the Hayes is located, volunteered washing 
and drying machines in an attempt to save the 90 costumes used in the show. The 
cause of the fire was not immediately determined. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Hutton 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
