<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROMEO BEATEN IN FINAL OF BOWLING EVENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
FAYETTEVILLE, Ga. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jeri Edwards defeated top-seeded Robin Romeo of Van Nuys, 244-169, on Thursday 
night to win her first career title and the $6,000 first prize in the $35,000 
Ladies Pro Bowlers Tour Greater Atlanta Open. 
</P>
<P>
Edwards opened with six strikes to build a lead that Romeo, the 1989 Woman 
Bowler of the Year, could not overcome. 
</P>
<P>
Romeo earned $3,000 for second place. 
</P>
<P>
Carol Norman started the final round with a 197-174 victory over Jeanne Maiden. 
Edwards then defeated Norman, 207-201, and Stacy Rider, 244-237, to advance to 
the title match. 
</P>
<P>
Rider earned $2,000 for third place, Norman won $1,700 for fourth and Maiden 
$1,500 for fifth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042790-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 210361 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 27, 1990, Friday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
226 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
L.A. BROADCASTER WILL BUY KJQY-FM FOR $20 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS KRAUL, SAN DIEGO COUNTY BUSINESS EDITOR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Legacy Broadcasting of Los Angeles has agreed to purchase KJQY, an 
easy-listening format FM station in San Diego, for $20 million, sources said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Legacy Chairman Carl E. Hirsch confirmed that a sale is due to close in May but 
declined to discuss the price. 
</P>
<P>
The seller is Command Communications based in Dallas, which acquired the 
station in January. A previously announced deal to sell the station to Westwood 
One, a broadcasting-publishing concern in Los Angeles, fell through. 
</P>
<P>
KJQY, or "KJOY" as it is known, currently has an easy adult listening format. 
It scored a 5.3% market share in the most recent Arbitron audience survey 
ratings, ninth best among San Diego FM stations. 
</P>
<P>
Hirsch said that format changes are in the offing for the station to make it 
appeal to younger audiences but he declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
Last December, Hirsch's Legacy chain sold all 10 of its stations, including 
KTWV-FM of Los Angeles, to Group W as part of a complex $727-million merger, 
one of the largest deals ever in radio broadcasting. Legacy remains a 15% 
shareholder in Group W. The rest is owned by Westinghouse Electric. 
</P>
<P>
Legacy is also in escrow to buy two other stations, WMJI-FM in Cleveland and 
WYHY-FM in Nashville from Jacor Communications for $31.25 million. All three 
station purchases will close simultaneously, Hirsch said Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
