<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
W. GERMANY'S GENSCHER HONORED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OVIEDO, Spain 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher was awarded the Prince of 
Asturias International Cooperation prize today for seeking disarmament in 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
Leopolodo Calvo Sotelo, the Prince of Asturias Foundation secretary and former 
Spanish prime minister, said Genscher won the award for "his vital contribution 
to the building of the European community, for his decisive role in the process 
of disarmament, for his efforts to create a Pan-European security system and 
for his tenacious defense of human rights." 
</P>
<P>
The prize is named after Prince Felipe de Borbon, heir to the Spanish throne. 
It carries a $47,500 prize. 
</P>
<P>
Other finalists were South African anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela and 
Czech president and playwright Vaclav Havel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
