<SECTION>
<P>
Orange County Life; Part N; Page 2; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
320 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY LIBRARY VIDEO CIRCULATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Kathie Bozanich and Janice L. Jones / Los Angeles 
Times; Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If video circulation at the county's public libraries is any indication, some 
of the bloom may be off home movie viewing. Between 1988 and 1989, circulation 
of videocassettes declined 2% -- this after a 6% increase between 1987 and 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
Videos circulate in 27 branches of the county public library, and during 1989 
there were declines from 1988 at 14 of them. 
</P>
<P>
The La Habra branch circulated 51,156 movies (or 8% of the county total) in 
1989, the most at any location. In terms of a single community, though, Irvine 
viewers were busiest, checking out nearly 72,000 movies at the city's two 
branches -- nearly 40% more than the three branches in Garden Grove and 83% 
more than Costa Mesa's two libraries. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
